Vice President Biden met with President Juan Manuel Santos of Colombia to discuss bilateral cooperation and the next steps in the Colombian peace process. Biden congratulated Santos on the approval of the peace accord and praised the Colombian people for their determination to reclaim their country. The Vice President reaffirmed the United States' commitment to support the implementation of the peace accords, including demobilization and disarmament of FARC combatants, protection of victims' rights, and application of the transitional justice framework. Biden emphasized the importance of engaging critics of the peace accord and focusing on counternarcotics to maintain and broaden support for the agreement. Both leaders expressed optimism for a peaceful hemisphere after 52 years of violence. The United States has committed $450 million in foreign assistance to implement the "Peace Colombia" strategy.